title: For Sale:  Awesome MI SSK12 - Comes Loaded with Optic & Every Upgrade You Could Want
postcontent:
This is easily the nicest rifle you'll find on here for the money, and likely almost anywhere else one may look. For those not familiar with the MI SSK12 Minute Man rifle, it is an AR-15 that comes with a great and very nice looking billet receiver set made by MI. Though a great rifle out of the box, I made many upgrades to better accommodate my needs for competition shooting. With the upgrades that have been made, you're buying a rifle that you would be hard pressed to further improve upon at a price less than that of the stock rifle, not to mention the $1000+ (far more with sales tax included) I have invested in the rifle through improvements and upgrades after purchasing the rifle new in October 2013

Among these upgrades are a brand new 16" 1:7 twist DRD hammer forged chrome lined barrel that I had installed in place of the original barrel in early June (poor timing on my part but at the time I had no plans to move abroad). The rifle has been taken to the range twice since installing this new barrel with roughly 100-200 rounds having been fired. The reason for switching barrels was to improve accuracy as the DRD uses polygonal rifling as well as being cold hammer forged. The accuracy with this new barrel is easily sub-MOA, quite possibly closer to 1/2 MOA. Other upgrades include the Magpul UBR Stock, Magpul Pro Sights, a Fortis compensator/muzzle brake, and a Geissele Super Dynamic Enhanced Flat two-stage trigger with a smooth 2 lb. first stage and a crisp 1.5 lb. second stage (Note that the Geissele trigger is not pictured as it was just installed and the trigger shown in the pictures is a Timney). The rifle originally came with a shorter 13" rail, but I had this replaced with a new MI Gen 2 quad rail when the new barrel was recently installed. A Weaver 1-5x tactical scope with offset mount and a Sight Docter mini red-dot sight is also included. Another nice feature is the upgraded BCG which is a Titanium Boron (TiN) Bolt Carrier Group. You can see the gold coloring of this BCG in the photos and in addition to improving the look, this bcg is very tough due to this coating, quite easy to clean and maintain, and functions flawlessly. 

As I'm preparing to move abroad where I will not have any use for my weapons, I'm selling two rifles, including this one, and one 1911 handgun. This rifle had originally sold for just over $1600 when I purchased it last fall and the value of the aforementioned upgrades has been well over $1,000. When you factor in the sales tax, this price is quite a bargain. The listing price of $1,550 includes the optic but I am willing to sell the rifle without the scope and with a JP single stage trigger for $1,450. Please let me know if you have any questions. Thanks! 

 UPGRADES
 -Billet Receiver Set - Not an upgrade but a very nice feature rare in even high end ARs.
 -New 16" DRD Cold Hammer Forged Chrome Lined Barrel with Polygonal Rifling
 -Magpul UBR Stock
 -Magpul Pro Backup Sights
 -Fortis Compensator/Muzzle Brake
 -Geissele Super Dynamic Enhanced Flat Two-Stage Trigger - Total 3lb. pull
 -Timney 3 lb. Adjustable Single-Stage Trigger is pictured but no longer installed
 -Replaced the stock 13" circular rail with a Gen 2 15" Quad Rail by MI
 -Upgraded BCG to a Titanium Boron (TiN) Bolt Carrier Group - Looks great with the gold 
 shine and is much harder to prevent damage and make cleaning very easy.
 -Optic is a Weaver 1-5x tactical scope with offset mount and a Sight Docter mini red-dot.

title: For Sale:  Ultra Compact Adjustable Stock (UCAS) - MP5 style stock similar to NEA PDW or M231 stock
postcontent:
I have a number of these very short MP5 style stocks for sale.  I'd been looking for something like this for some time but was unable to find anything close that also functioned well.  You can see how this stock looks in the pic of my new SBR below.  
Included with purchase is the stock, castle nut, receiver end plate, two different sized shoulder rests, and the custom buffer spring system that enables your rifle to function with just a 3.5 inch buffer.  This buffer spring system is compatible with any mil-spec bcg.  With respect to the two shoulder rests that may be attached to the stock, one is larger one and one is just over half that size small (very similar in size to that of the NEA).  The larger one is pictured on my SBR while the smaller one may be pictured in other pics or I’m happy to provide additional photos.  In my opinion this smaller rest wasn't as comfortable and didn't provide enough shoulder support but to each their own.
Please contact me if you're interested.  I'm happy to ship within the U.S. as well for a cost of $25 for priority shipping, though clearly willing to negotiate for larger orders.  Also happy to accommodate bulk or mini-bulk orders at significant discounts.  At this point I’m simply testing the waters to gauge interest, market size, and  conservative growth expectations to determine whether this is in fact a viable opportunity worth a more meaningful investment.  I had these stocks created after searching and searching for a similar stock and while I found a few used M231 stocks, used NEA stocks, and a few others but the asking prices were $500+ with many including no extra buffer systems required to use the stock, thus creating an additional cost of $100 to $300 depending on the system.                                
Coincidentally, after I’d been on the NEA waitlist for 6-8 months and had lost faith that they were in fact going to continue with production, I received an email earlier today that NEA is again taking orders.  Thankfully the price has come down a bit and hopefully they will have ironed out previous capacity constraints that seemed to hinder production. Further information is provided through the following link:  http://www.theammosource.com/index.php?main_page=product_info&products_id=2177                
Though I have not had personal experience with the new LWRC Stock found on their new PDW: IC PSD, I find few of their products to be subpar.  Unfortunately this stock will not be sold individually, or this isn’t in the cards in the foreseeable future.  I also wish they would use this stock on more than just the 6.8.  You can see some images and a little info through the following link:  http://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2012/11/27/new-pdw-from-lwrc-ic-psd/  
Having been discouraged in my search, I approached a local plastics and aerospace manufacturer who in turn made several introductions to factories willing to accommodate my needs of building a functional, minimalist stock that can stand up to abuse, and have an attractive look. After an initial prototype, we made a few changes and came up with the product pictured.  Should you purchase a stock, I would greatly appreciate any thoughts on ways to further improve the stock in any way.
Discounted rates begin with orders as small as 5 stocks and pricing information for larger orders is outlined below.  I’m also open to unique arrangements that may be mutually beneficial so if you have an ideas or proposals, just let me know and I will do my best to accommodate.  Thanks.
Orders of:
	1 - 4 Units @ $350/unit
	5 - 10 Units @ $335/unit
	11 - 25 Units @ $315/unit
	26 - 50 Units @ $300/unit
	51+ Units Negotiable but will not exceed $275/unit
Again, each unit ordered includes the stock, castle nut, end plate, and custom short buffer system compatible with any mil-spec standard bcg (I'm happy to provide additional info on the buffer system upon request).

title: For Sale:  MAB Model D 7.65mm/.32acp
postcontent: I am selling a .32acp semi-auto pistol. It is a MAB Model D. MAB is an acronym for a French company that translates to Manufacture of Arms of Bayonne. The MAB Model D is modeled after the FN/Browning Model 1922. MAB made very good quality pistols. This is a milsurp pistol manufactured between 1945 and 1953, I believe. This gun has the "palm tree" mark on the trigger guard to indicate it was a military or police pistol in Morocco. The palm tree makes this a collector's item. It has a 9+1 capacity and comes with one magazine. There are three safeties. The first is the thumb lever on the left side of the slide forward of the grip. The second is the grip safety on the back of the frame. The third is the magazine safety. It has target grips and a target rear sight, for import I believe. If the grips and the sight are replaced with the original type this becomes a very slim pistol. As it is this pistol would be excellent for training a new shooter with its good grip, sight picture, and light recoil. All numbered parts match the gun. I am asking $225 cash.

title: For Sale:  Mako FAB Defense MWG Magwell Grip with SERIAL NUMBER WINDOW
postcontent:
NEW MWG FAB Defense Black Magazine Well Grip  $20







This accessory acts as a comfortable forward vertical grip and a magazine well funnel for quick magazine changes. Manufactured from reinforced polymer composite, it is lightweight and extremely durable. Unlike some ugly aftermarket magwell funnels, the MWG looks good on any rifle.  NEW CONDITION, But may not be in original packaging.







This is the model with the serial number window.







The MWG is designed in two halves that are placed around the magazine well. Three hex screws hold the two halves together. It extends below the magazine well to form an effective funnel to speed reloads. The front is finger-grooved and textured for a comfortable, secure hold, and the additional width give a more comfortable grip than the bare receiver. For those who worry that hand pressure on a magazine could cause malfunctions (I have never seen this happen), the MWG keeps the hand off of the magazine.

Because there are slight variations in civilian lower receivers between manufacturers in the US, the MWG may require slight fitting for some lowers. The most common differences are in the size of the lip at the magwell opening and the radius below the pivot pin. We have found it to be a drop-in fit on some receivers, while others need a bit of dremel work on the grove that fits the bottom of the magazine well, or a bit of file work on the part of the MWG that fits under the pivot pin. We have even seen variations between receivers from the same manufacturers, with the MWG fitting some of their lowers but needing adjustment for others.  Rifles with recievers that are radically different in shape from the milspec pattern may require extensive fitting or may not work with the MWG.

Not compatible with Beta-C Twin Drum Mags or Magpul 10 round magazines.
